        Official Singles Chart on 26/7/2019

        26 July 2019 - 1 August 2019

        The Official UK Singles Chart reflects the UK’s biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1 and MTV, the Top 100 is published exclusively on OfficialCharts.com. View the biggest songs of 2024 so far.

        My thoughts & observations on the UK charts as always…

        ‘Senorita’ by Shawn Mendes & Camila Cabello returns to the top of the singles chart for its second week at #1! It accumulated over 68,000 chart sales this week, consisting of 9,200 downloads & 8 million streams.

        ‘Senorita’ also spends a second consecutive week at #1 on the national airplay chart.
        http://ukairplaychart.com/

        ‘Old Town Road [Remix]’ by Lil Nas X ft Billy Ray Cyrus has now been #1 on Britain’s YouTube chart for the past 14 weeks, with roughly no change in views at around 3.75 million.
        https://charts.youtube.com/charts/TopSongs/gb?hl=en-gb

        Elsewhere, in the US, ‘Old Town Road’ is looking likely to become the longest Billboard Hot 100 #1 of all-time this Monday (17 weeks).

        SAM SMITH - HOW DO YOU SLEEP? (#12)
        Sam Smith seems to have a much longer single rollout than most big artists have recently & essentially the opposite to what Ed Sheeran just did, since it’s been months since ‘Dancing With A Stranger’ became big! Although with this, I’m sorry, it doesn’t come close in all honesty. I always said that ‘Dancing WIth A Stranger’ was an amazing song & would be a hard act to follow, but there were clearly risks being taken here, which sadly didn’t pay off in my opinion. I can’t even blame Sam for that though, since he carries a level of charisma & a good sense of his rhythm on his part, but this is also trying to go into both a 90s R&B direction, as well as a more poppy one, but trying to stick to both of those lanes kind of made this song a lot more messy than it needed to me. The bigger issue comes in the post-chorus drop, where the squawking effects drown out almost every other feature here & the underlying beat isn’t even in time with that at some parts! I can absolutely get behind how relatable the lyrics are, especially for people whose partners have cheated on them, but Sam Smith’s done this sort of thing a lot better in the past. Light 5/10!

        ELLIE GOULDING & JUICE WRLD - HATE ME (#36)
        No joke, I’ve heard this so much across so many different radio channels, that I thought it already hit the Top 40 & that I reviewed it! Anyway, I guess that’s a good sign that the song could have some staying power. As for the song itself, eh, it’s decent, but far from Ellie Goudling’s best. I do feel that this is a good pairing when it comes to hearing both sides of a toxic relationship, but it’s clear that Ellie Goulding completely outshines Juice WRLD here, since the former captures that emotion & tension amazing well, especially in that falsetto, while the latter provides his usual warbled tone. I guess this could’ve developed into something more given the dark & creepy production, especially with the bass hitting notably harder in the second half of the chorus, except the hook is just too repetitive & lacked effort in my opinion. I mean, I’m still pleased that Ellie Goulding could be about to get another hit, but I just wish it was something on the same level of quality as say ‘Burn’ or ‘Love Me Like You Do’, that’s all. Solid 6/10!

        JOEL CORRY - SORRY (#38)
        Unlike other songs that have been on Love Island, I feel like this one would probably have got this high anyway even if it didn’t (& trust me, this will climb a fair bit further up the chart!). As for this, it certainly has all the essential ingredients to become a midsummer banger, but I’m not sure how well they’re all mixed together. I think where Joel Corry went right straight away was the clever fusion of a jaunty piano, as well as bringing house back to the dance scene. The female vocals also seem to be mixed perfectly into both of these production aspects. However, despite a promising beat, the hook does fall a little bit flat for me to be honest, since I don’t think it’s going to bring the hype in the clubs or dancefloors that it’s going for. That being said, it’s not far off at all & since I’ve not talked about this guy before, I’d be curious to see what he does next. As it is, light 7/10 for this!

        LIL TECCA - RAN$OM (#40)
        When I did my research into this & found out it was from a young trap MC who I never heard of, I didn’t have the biggest expectations for this… however, while it didn’t take me too long to see some appeal, it’s definitely not for me. I get that loads of people, including me, are getting so tired of monotonous & auto-tuned vocal editing, but I think that Lil Tecca does it in a way where the melody at least becomes a bit more laid-back & less annoying. I also feel like that’s partly helped by the gentle sparkle in the production too. However, I do find the irony comes into the content, where Lil Tecca mentions that he’ll take other rappers for ransom if they steal his flow, yet his delivery sounds extremely similar to something A Boogie Wit Da Hoodie would try. Other than that, it’s just another dose of cheap brand name bragging & flubbed rhymes, so while you’re not missing much, it’s at least tolerable coming from a 16-year-old rapper, but still, Light 5/10 here!

        On the albums chart, Ed Sheeran is #1 for a second week in a row with ‘No.6 Collaborations Project’. It has roughly an equal split of sales & streaming (including 41% physical sales). Once again, it outsold the rest of the Top 5 combined!

        Speaking of which, the rest of the Top 5 is: ‘Divinely Uninspired To A Hellish Extent’ by Lewis Capaldi (stationary at #2), Freya Ridings’ self-titled debut album (debuts at #3), ‘When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?’ by Billie Eilish (3-4) & ‘Anima’ by Thom Yorke (debuts at #5).
        https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/albums-chart/

        Looking ahead to next week, these songs could enter the Top 40 for the first time: ‘The Archer’ by Taylor Swift, ‘Gold Roses’ by Rick Ross ft Drake, ‘I Could Get Used To This’ by Becky Hill & Weiss, ‘Bad Behaviour’ by Mabel, ‘Good As ’ by Lizzo, 'Outnumbered' by Dermot Kennedy & maybe even more.

        Thanks for reading everyone! I hope you all have a good weekend. :)

        My latest Crown Note chart: http://crownnote.com/charts/piran-delves/pirans-top-40-139

        Now continuing on Finland in WWII. As a history freak this might get spammed but I'm trying to keep this fairly basic :D

        So it all tied down to the end of WWI. Russian Empire fell, and the Soviet Union emerged. The Grand Duchy of Finland, officially a part of the Russian Empire, saw its opportunity among the chaos, and declared independence on December 6, 2017, with support from Vladimir Lenin himself.

        However that only created chaos. Finland in early 1918 was heavily divided into two camps: the first one being the senate of Finland and its supporters, officially called the "Whites", and the rebels who went against the senate, officially called the "Reds". These inner battles then started the Civil War of Finland, with the Whites gaining support from Imperial Germany, and the Reds having support from Soviet Union. While the war lasted only from January 2018 until May 2018 and ended in the Whites' victory, it was very very !

        While it was never calm between the World Wars, Finland held on with a few political crisis but nothing too major.

        However then came the Molotov-Ribbentrop pact in August 1938. In the pact the Baltic States, the Eastern Poland and Finland were "given" to the Soviets as a frontier. While the Baltic states voluntarily gave the Soviets access to military bases, Finland didn't surrender that easily. Despite numerous negotiations, the Winter War began in November 1939, when the Soviets shot the "Mainila Shots", a series of gunshots which Soviet soldiers themselves shot and then claimed that Finland had shot them, considering this as an act of war.

        The war lasted from November 1939 until the Moscow peace treaty in March 1940, and was fought in Eastern Finland. Terms like "Sisu", an untranslatable term meaning the special Finnish willpower, and Molotov Cocktail were created. Among most interesting facts in the war were the extremely cold winter climates, huge losses of the Red Army, the Finnish fighting tactics and the "Spirit of Talvisota".

        While it officially ended as a stalemate, Finland had to give 11% of its territories to the Soviets, including then-second-largest city Viipuri. Then again Finland did fight really well against an unbeatable Red Army. The Soviets most likely considered Finland as an easy target and that the victory would be easy!
